<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-247-023 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 754 333</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Jan 7 1991 n302 p55(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Product management: a new approach to fully realize potential MISbenefits. (Final Word) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McGuinness, James A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The process-oriented approach used by many MIS departments blindsthem to broader management issues and benefits.andP;  A productmanagement approach can overcome obstacles to the fast developmentof applications that are flexible enough to change as businessconditions change.andP;  Standardizing on the parts used inmanufacturing allowed companies in the 1970s to lower productioncosts.andP;  MIS must extend the concepts of modularity and reusabilityto development of applications using standardized components andpackaging.andP;  Rather than having 'applications' supplemented by'toolkits', MIS would instead have various standardized objectsused by applications and tools, such as coordinate groupwareobjects and interface objects.andP;  New measures of MIS success areneeded that are more like market-driven measurements of a productmanagement approach; the benefits of such an approach aredescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISManagement of EDPUser RelationsQuality ControlApplications ProgrammingProgram Development TechniquesManagement StyleNew TechniqueManagement/EDP Relations.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>